name: SCG Embedding Toolkit for Version 1.5 Models - A collection of tools and helpers from my personal kit
description:
Over the last 6 months, I've created quite the collection of helper and tool embeds for doing things like fixing faces, pushing realism, creating anime scenes, making subjects smile, or cry, or face the camera, whatever. Rather than creating separate listings for the literal dozens of tools I have, I've decided instead to just create a "master" listing for all of my tools that I can then update whenever I have new tools to add.

Unlike some of my more grand embeddings out there, many of these serve simple purposes and are of limited effect by themselves. Some are little more than funny experiments that turned into something useful, while others were created as helpers as part of a larger project.

I will continue to update this listing as I create more tools. I'm not planning on exposing my ENTIRE toolbox, just the ones I use and share with friends most frequently.

Don't expect a lot of demo images or a lot of fanfare on this listing. This is my toolkit. If you want to use my tools, please, be my guest, but I make no guarantee of results - Sometimes they work great, sometimes they don't, the fun part is finding the best mix to get the results you want!

As with all of my other embeds, my tools are designed to be mixed with my other 1.5 compatible embeds available on my profile page. Mix and match for some really interesting outputs, and follow me here on Civit to be notified when I release new embeddings!

--------

To use these embeddings in AUTOMATIC1111, copy them to your embeddings folder in your stable-diffusion-webui directory. No need to restart, just invoke the embedding from your prompt. Make sure you are using a 1.5 version compatible model or you will get errors!

--------

modelVersions.name: No512 - Remove Annoyances
modelVersions.description: No512 is my attempt to remove the stuff that tends to show up too much and ruins otherwise good output. Think glasses, masks, hats, necklaces and shine. You can still prompt this stuff back in just fine in my experience, this just reduces that tendency for SD to randomly throw this stuff in by itself. It's scope is limited, most of the modern models are good enough at avoiding the annoyances anyway, but it still serves its purpose. YMMV

modelVersions.name: Neg_Realism512
modelVersions.description: Use this embedding in your negative prompt - Neg_realism512 gooses output towards more realistic, nicer, more cinematic style output. Use it when you're attempting hyperreal or photoreal output as a boost. The effect is subtle, but it does work. The samples I used are purposely heavy handed (calling a painting style in the prompt) but it shows what it does. Use it to goose realism!

modelVersions.name: Neg_Anime512
modelVersions.description: Use this embedding in your negative prompt - This embedding boosts anime output. It won't "create" an anime style on its own, but will instead further enhance anime (or really any animated or cartoon style) output. It works well with the anime variants (Av3, WD, BerryMixes, etc.) that I've tested. As with the other tools in my toolkit, the effect is subtle by itself, but its there!

modelVersions.name: Beauty512
modelVersions.description: This embedding just makes people look better. nicer faces, fuller features. Works on males and females both. It can also have an effect on scenes as well, so if you're trying to make ugly awful scenes, best leave this one on the shelf! This may have a tendency to make people strip, so either add "nudity" to your negative prompt or describe the clothing you want your subjects to wear!

modelVersions.name: Awful512
modelVersions.description: Awful512 does what the name implies. It makes things ugly. Has a stronger effect on adult subjects than children. Should work for both males and females without changing sex that I've noticed. I like to use this when creating apocalyptic scenes, or when working with monsters or just want to make a scene look a bit more grungy and dirty. It's subtle, but it works, just like my other tools.

modelVersions.name: neg_facelift512
modelVersions.description: Use this embedding in your negative prompt - This embed makes faces nicer and cleaner. Will remove dirt and yuck out of a scene as it works as a beautifier, so don't use it if you're trying to chase ugly, messy, or dirty scenes. I'll be honest, all of the really great models for 1.5 now do a good job of making nice faces already, so this may be of limited benefit compared to the 2.1 version, but still handy to have in the kit!

modelVersions.name: Selfie512
modelVersions.description:
-FOR BEST RESULTS USE AT START OF PROMPT-
Selfie512 does as the name implies, it gets your subjects up close, arm up, smiling for the camera. An unfortunate side effect of the embed will sometimes put a cell phone in your subject's hand. You can try negging "cell phone" and "mirror shot", but honestly, it's a quirk of the pose, just reroll if you don't like it. Another thing, sometimes you get selfie sticks. I haven't found a good way to prevent those yet, but thankfully don't happen too often.

modelVersions.name: Neg512
modelVersions.description: Neg512 is my attempt at creating a proper negative prompt that makes output nicer without changing styles. Expect richer colors, clearer subjects and less AI weirdness. Based on my excellent Neg_Realism512, all style modifiers have been removed, leaving a negative that can be applied across pretty much any style (yet to find an incompatible style) - As with all my tools, YMMV, but this has become my go-to "always add" negative, which I then supplement with my other negative embeds as needed. This embed should work for any 1.5 derivative model without any problems.

modelVersions.name: Neg_Hands512
modelVersions.description: My take on a hand fixing negative embed. I've noticed a lot of the other hand fixers cause subjects to hide their hands and fingers (typically because they've added the word "hand" and "fingers" to their negative prompt) - Neg_Hands512 works a bit differently - Rather than focusing on messed up hands and fingers and limbs, I instead focus on the negative aspects of those messed up hands, targeting negative words like "stubby, deformed, polydactyl, mangled, amputated.." etc. THIS IS NOT A TRAINED EMBEDDING - Meaning that it shouldn't affect the style of your images. It's also not perfect, you're still going to get the occasional AI hand oddness, but it does help. YMMV, no guarantee of course, but I use it constantly and you should too!
